A Republican strategy to hinder Obama’s re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight voter fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and states that voter fraud is less prevalent in the United States than the number of people who die from lightning strikes.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: those new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what happens in Canada, the American states are responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
And in the same vein, a majority of American governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that made the registration or voting process difficult.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the rise of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 restricting the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity card with a photograph, in addition to a proof of American citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of the ballot and withdraw the right to vote from citizens with criminal records.
Prior to the 2006 election, no American state required voters to present a photo ID.
The State of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The Supreme Court of the United States upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
As a result, the Republican authorities were quick to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to keep in mind that, contrary to what happens in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as the Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack such an identity document.
But, often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
Twenty-five per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 and 20 per cent of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states, students, the voters who vote the most for Democratic candidates, cannot use their institution’s photo ID.
On the other hand, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use the documents issued by those clubs.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to make such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
It appears that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers supported in 2011 certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day of the ballot in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a service to help voters who would like to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 brought the registration rate for new voters down in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers adopted laws in five other states that favored reducing the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida election, 33% of voters who voted ahead were African-American, while the latter accounted for no more than 13% of the state’s voters.
In the case of Hispanics, the same thing happened.
These represent only 11% of voters, which is equivalent to 24% of citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who make up 76% of the electorate, make up no more than 46% of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have fervently opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney’s Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
It was possible, in part, to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they are intended to influence the results of 2012 in key states.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that states that have adopted such laws account for 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these electoral-system-scale legislative changes will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: those new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
