The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated quite a stir last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what’s more, it’s about the particle whose existence the standard model predicted: our best or “least bad” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has yet to be empirically observed.
But it’s not entirely clear to physicists that these are Higgs.
We know without a doubt that a new particle exists and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data revealed this week at a major physics congress held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data is still missing to be completely sure.
Anyway, we assume that it is Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem few. We will see what it is about.
There is, in this great world, a generalized and inescapable law which implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There’s no way to break that rule and don’t try too hard, because you’ll end up hurting yourself.
Although the physics of particles is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, roughly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called fermions, who obey wisely the principle of Pauli.
And then there are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to Berkeley Laboratories’ The Particle Adventure website, which, by the way, is extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we won’t talk about here, and the “force particles,” by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, one might underline here, are not the exotic bugs we might believe.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the “light particle” that acts as a “messenger” of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (of light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing more than a photon; that is, one of the "force-bearing" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, that needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it you need to reach extremely high energies, a little like an icy pond in which only a thick rock could slide on the surface.
That’s why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN (the big hadron collider is a 27 km ring!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles or all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don’t: a piece of paper, for example, will never by itself stick to a fridge door.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not.
Now, what “can” all these investigations bring?, asks Mrs. Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between MS observations and predictions.
For their part, many fervently desire that they meet, because the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that covers certain holes of the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (another ups!).
But we have not found such differences at CERN so far.
Implications
The repercussions of such investigations in our day to day are difficult to predict, but we do not think that we are wrong to say that it will not have any.
For you to see: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of lasers in laboratories did not suspect at all the revolution that their work would provoke.
They glimpsed scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as the physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who produced the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, already said, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
Imagine...
And in addition, applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light collector in 1969 in the course of his research into optics.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this sensor now serves as an "eye" for all digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
That does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but that we never know...
