53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadboisarrivent center come from home and 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
Seventy-seven per cent of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e., care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient reaches the terminal stage of life, whether at home, in the hospital or in a care facility.
And several agencies, such as the Victor-Gadbois center and the Grand Montréal home palliative care society, specialize almost exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great relative lack of health care in Quebec that makes many doctors specialized in palliative care fear the adoption of a law that regulates euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by eminences of palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health system is not competent enough to ensure that anyone is entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
"Recently," she says, "I've seen a patient spend 14 days in the ER in great pain without being able to relieve it.
I fear patients will want to die just because they don’t get the proper care.”
And at the same time, many oncologists persist with their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
