A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever regarding the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
It caught everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when it announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given two more months to the Assembly to finish its work.
And Egypt has been using a provisional text for almost two years, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial imbroglios.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
To his opponents, the president perseveres in his “autocratic delirium” and continues to “betray his word” and “step on the right.”
Supporters say it is a move to end the institutional and political crisis faster and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short span of time that forces the Brethren to give up their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to recover popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy wreaks havoc throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote in his favor, as he claimed in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "either vote my text or I maintain full powers", powers that supposedly will come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist in its great majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not attend the call.
In mid-November, a little before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt that they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society followed suit.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 substitute members were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As might be expected, the articles voted on were unanimous.
Commentators are amused, on the other hand, by the fact that one of the few discrepancies of the day was expressed practically at the hour of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the clock of the Constituent Assembly was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the object of all eyes, remains finally identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that “the principles of Sharia constitute the principal source of law”.
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that “principles” could be replaced by “rules,” which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their good will and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it nothing more than a publicity stunt.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its conformity with Sharia laws.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because “people called to speak out are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy."
Liberals’ fears are further heightened by the fact that the university’s next chancellor would be considerably less moderate than the current one.
“For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are in the framework of civil status.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system,” explains Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around Article 220, as the terms used mimic the religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that could be asked in the future would be to what extent are the civil judges competent to pronounce themselves above all this.”
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms that refer to the extended powers it confers on the president of the Republic.
The Muslim Brethren will claim that they are few compared to what they were during the previous regime.
Another point of contention: the powers conferred on the army.
According to the desire of the military, the revision of the defense budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defense council.
Nor will prosecutions of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as human rights associations called for.
They also expressed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy continues and henceforth insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
Moreover, no article emphasizes the protection of women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was due to go on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this noon.
Supporters of the head of state demonstrated on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the holy land, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the majesty of biblical truths with modern comfort and pristine nature.
“AIF” identified the five most important reasons why Israel should be visited.
Reverence in the Holy Land
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone who enters this "baptismal font" will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of Jesus’ miracles: the conversion of water into wine at the wedding, walking on the waters, the appeasement of the storm and the crowded nets.
In this same place, Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
But the greatest number of holy places is found in Jerusalem.
Believers travel here the Via Crucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin "Via Dolorosa").
It begins at Antony’s Fortress, the Praetorium, where the trial took place, and continues through the streets of the Old City, going to the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha Mount, the site of the crucifixion, to the Anointing Stone, and to the burial place of Jesus.
In this same place is also the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built on the spot where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred site for Jews, the Western Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
As is tradition, people of different religions leave notes here with their wishes, which will then come true.
Take a vertical trip
The ruins of the Masada Fortress were what remained of a secret shelter against enemies, which Herod the Great had built in 25 BC for his family.
They are located on mountain cliffs at a height of 450 m above sea level.
And get there by your own means, only those who are dedicated to climbing can.
Others can reach this historic summit on the funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous ski resort Hermon, where in the winter months there is a large influx of tourists.
Bus services are offered from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, on top of the mountain supposedly inhabited pagan gods.
Visit unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
In a single trip you will not be able to visit them all.
But it is worth visiting at least five of them, the most interesting.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
It preserves the ancient Dead Sea Scrolls or Qumran Scrolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological pieces.
It is worth visiting the Museum of Art in Tel Aviv.
In his exhibition of paintings he has canvases by Impressionists and Expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the Al Basha museum-bathroom, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Caesarea it is worth stopping by the exclusive private Ralli museum, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tour guides or souvenir shops there.
Admission is free, and donations are categorically not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section is the Children’s Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars are shining.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they lost their lives ring out.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health
The three main tourist areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of them there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that in the Red Sea they bathe even in the winter months, since the temperature of the water does not fall below 21 degrees and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there they bathe throughout the year.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is located at the lowest point on the planet: at 417 m below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that easily hold even those who do not know how to swim.
The surrounding landscapes are truly beautiful.
People come here to pass courses of treatment with salt water, brine and healing muds and to fortify their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to put their broken nerves in order.
Touching the Mysteries of Antiquity
They are preserved in the old part of Tel Aviv, the citadel of Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
It passed through the famous sea route linking Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this same place, he led a long and happy life.
Tourists love to stroll through the narrow streets bearing the names of the Zodiac signs.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of your "same" symbol, fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa you can find newlywed couples who come from all over Israel, and even from other countries to get photographed.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the principal city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists remember
If you travel to Israel, don’t worry if your English leaves much to be desired: in this country around 30% of the population speaks Russian.
The money for this trip is not recommended to take it in euros, but in dollars, which can easily be changed to shekels (currently 1-3$,8 shekels).
Urban transport is mainly made up of buses, but in Jerusalem there is fast tram and in Haifa is the only metro line in the country, which consists of six stations and connects the Lower City with the Upper City.
Actually, it's from an underground funicular.
Traveling on any type of public transport costs 6 shekels and for this price you can travel by transferring for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturdays.
From Friday night to Saturday sunset, markets and shops close and public transport disrupts their work.
But on Sunday morning a new work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes in which milk and meat are combined.
There is a wide selection of dishes based on beef and lamb, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a variety of sauces, phalafel, which are balls of ground chickpea, fruits and vegetables.
Street dogs are not seen on the streets of Israeli cities.
Instead, there are many well-fed cats that “walk as they please” in imposing ways.
At night you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Snorers love crowded places and don’t reject treats.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost $37 (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) a day.
In addition to insurance, it comes out for $15 a day.
And the rent of a bicycle will go for 15 shekels a day.
Museum tickets cost an average of 30 shekels.
Israel in figures
In 2012 more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of those who came to tour the country and rest were citizens of the US, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, the United Kingdom and Ukraine.
The Promised Land, from January to October 2012, was visited by 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists, a number that exceeds by 51% the same rate of 2010, before the cancellation of the visa regime on February 9, 2011.
'The Great and Powerful' Will Take You to Moscow: Immigrants Save for Language
While deputies and human rights defenders discuss the consequences of the law on compulsory examination, scammers who trade with “false” certificates have already appeared in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
They are mostly citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed home.
Since December 1, a law comes into force, according to which each immigrant worker must take an exam to check his knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service delivery sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, over time, as promised in the Federal Immigration Service, the exams will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will not be enough to take the language exam, but also the one of Russian history and the one of fundamentals of the legislation.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed even to receive and renew the work permit.
Exceptions are citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Persons who succeeded in obtaining their education certificates and diplomas prior to the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 shall not be subject to this law.
Utility, fatality and defense of rights
The network of examination centres will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, Peoples’ Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take part in the tests in all cities, now more than 160 such centers are open in Russia.
The initiative on the introduction of the examination was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and by the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights advocates, long before the law went into effect, often managed to ask this question to the press: And what will this actually bring?
What changes will the obligatory knowledge of the language bring, both for Russians and for immigrants themselves?
First, respond the representatives of the Immigration Service, this will reduce the number of people suffering "labour slavery".
Many people today talk about defending the rights of labor immigrants, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Russian Federal Immigration Service in Tajikistan.
The defense of your rights must begin before your departure.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of cases.
The problems are faced by immigrants without profession, education, those who do not know the language or pass medical control.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev says, the future immigrant will be doomed to find unscrupulous people who, under the pretext of helping, put a “paid trip” into a creepy, narrow covacha, where he and dozens of others like him are consumed for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We received countless complaints from our immigrants.
“In their homeland they promise them one thing, but when they arrive they are cheated, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised salaries,” confirms the Head of the Labour Immigration Directorate of the Tajikistan Immigration Service, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't be mad, bossy!
However, in the meantime many citizens of Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they intend to go to, but also write in their own language with difficulty.
Of course, this is not so much their fault but their own misfortune: there are few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks who can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families even have nothing to feed the children, not to mention dressing them, shoeing them and buying them what they need for school.
When they reach adolescence, these guys venture to work at the first opportunity.
It is difficult, if you do not know the language, to recognize them.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
However, when it comes to language law, rights advocates make an important point.
The exams will be conducted only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no examination and, consequently, no official work.
Meanwhile, most immigrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbidden passage to strangers"
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause is bureaucratic obstacles and the difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false inscription can be made quickly and for only fifteen hundred rubles.
The employees of the Russian police know that we usually carry false documents, we are not registered and extortion cases appear.
"They ask us for a hundred or two hundred rubles for cigarettes or tea," Tajik citizen Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be stingy, buy a painting"
On the first day of the entry into force of the language law, it became clear that not only immigrant registration documents may be false.
Several “false” certificates of knowledge of the language have already been seized by officials of the Federal Immigration Service.
The forged documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they came into the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the immigrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system against corruption so that “diplomas” cannot be bought, government officials and rights advocates converge.
So far, the authorities can promise immigrant workers that they would not have been able to successfully pass the exam the first time more time to study the basic course of the language.
In addition, immigrants who do not speak Russian will be offered jobs that do not require active communication with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not take drastic measures against the illegal arms trade
The percentage of crimes committed with registered weapons is quite low
The Ministry of the Interior proposes to apply the law more rigidly in relation to owners of weapons for civilian use.
This is the government’s reaction to the recent incidents: Squeezing shots during wedding celebrations in which fortunately there were no victims, and the massacre initiated by Moscow lawyer Dimitri Vinogradov, in which Squeezing seven people lost their lives.
Police want to ban the use and possession of traumatic weapons in public places and raise the minimum age for obtaining a gun license from 18 to 21.
This idea was supported by the head of the Duma committee on security and anti-corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that reforms in the law on gun possession will be taken to the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is happy with the fact that the Russian authorities are trying to counter this problem by applying the “heavy-handed policy”.
An open letter has appeared on the Internet, the authors of which, representatives of various social organizations of shooters, demand that such measures of "nonsense rigidity" be abandoned.
The percentage of vandalism involving registered weapons is minimal, Russian criminal lawyer Vasiliy Lésnikov told the BBC news service.
According to statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, during six months of 2012 142 crimes were committed with the use of firearms registered in internal organs, compared to the total of 1168 crimes registered for this same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that stricter legislation in the civil weapons sector will not be an inconvenience for the offender to target the black market.
Now, according to his words, in Moscow you can find any weapon at a low price.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior states that the situation of the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The black market for weapons is supplied through various channels.
The main channels are years, says retired colonel Victor Baranets, who for ten years worked in the Ministry of Education and the High Staff.
