The problems of reproduction in space with flora began to be addressed.
Experiments with plants have been carried out for half a century.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit differed in nothing from terrestrial varieties.
Then came the brood of insects in orbit, small fruit flies, the drosophiles.
In 1979 quail eggs were sent into space to check how the embryo develops under conditions of weightlessness.
We get a normal chick as a result.
But then the problems begin.
