Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled in the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to make a comparison without specific data; however, Germany is still a model in some respects, but it is not possible to specify exactly which is better.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
Of course not, but again, I don’t like to make this kind of comparison.
It is necessary to say that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If they didn't, they wouldn't benefit from collaborating with our office, would they?
With regard to the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public awards mean to your Office?
Since the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control proceedings.
Since we carry out ex-post checks, a certain delay is required.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing future controls: we have initiated a new tool of "non-economic risk detection", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, since the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and the like.
Do you consider that the adoption of this law is beneficial or that, rather, it is a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I believe that this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that can arise is that the regulation “hardens” and it is impossible to comply with it.
Under the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programmes of the regional council), and each law not respected in terms of public awards meant the violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to harden the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal failure, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create more bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this path takes us.
The prime minister has recently stated that the SDG would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called varc system, with reference to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the "varc" system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits something, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the action of the Office that has the obligation to carry out such checks and demand obligations.
He can say, “We changed the law and allowed it,” but he can’t say we’ll just do it.
In the law on public adjudications, the rules are quite strict as to how to act formally. And that is how they should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for not fulfilling the formal demands.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
