Poland and the Cosmos.
Poland was accepted as ESA’s twelfth member at last week’s meeting of ESA country ministers, the second member of ESA’s former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began an intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and over the following years participated in the agency’s project committee.
However, Poland’s path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in spaceflight before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld at the astronomical observatory in Warsaw in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the assistants indifferent and, years later, Oternfeld remembered that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Oternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, he was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he put his name to one of the craters on the far side of the moon.
As early as 1925 a dresina was built in Poland that was to be fitted with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and the details of the project are not known.
It is not clear if the rocket was to be used for the start of the drain or for its braking.
The information on this drain is limited to the information collected in the press of the time.
Beginning in 1933, Polish artillery began to devote itself to missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes clear that the investigation reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by the engineer Rohozi?ski appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpedo powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile technology projects for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the start of the war.
Other studies devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine first referenced society with four very extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, Prof. M. Suboticze, proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
From the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronautics Society (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Beginning in 1956, the PTA was significantly involved in the development of the successful RM (Rakieta Meteorologizna) sounding rocket, which became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 the air tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets began in the Bodów desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket in development was to be the object of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have an apogee of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
In 1962, however, work was suspended.
The successor to the first rockets of the RM type was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other by the space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum apogee in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first aerial tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were later built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland’s entry into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the COSPAR national committee two years later.
Within the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined the cosmic space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimír Remek.
The suspension of the social work law is not the solution.
Last week the Constitutional Court suspended the social work law.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulation.
Consequently, this means that different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, along with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labour costs (wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and to do so "causes a decrease" in the price of the competitor with the aim of taking the largest part of the market and, thus, increase its profit margin.
On a large scale it means, for most entrepreneurs, moving production abroad, buying there cheaper or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where the price of labor, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and, with it, is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the social spending of the state necessarily grows.
All this situation encourages the total lack of interest of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and compensate for the economic and social damages they have caused in their desire to obtain benefits.
The situation is universally so well known that it is not necessary to present specific statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of these countries are forced to compete with the objective of artificially reducing the social level of their own population and, in this way, attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own population without regard to social decline.
This is especially evident in the changes in the existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other, through the restricted right of employees in respect of labour rights.
The result is growing poverty along with the widening gap between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years now, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot support themselves with their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of aid is now one million.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there is a fairly frequent case: employed people with such a low salary that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum essential to survive.
A scandal of this kind related to the situation of the auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament was made public.
The savings measures of practically all the southern states of the EU lead, without a doubt, to the same situation. People, pressured by an abysmal decline in their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the nineteenth century or to live poorly on a lousy salary at the limit of society, in the hope that one day private investment capital will arrive in the country.
Do you have to wonder where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty passes from one country to another or never arrives, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a tiny part of a European salary.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media adamantly assert that the state should not bring capital to the economy, that running the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends tooth and nail the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by meddling in control.
Next, it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence with its egoism the political march and, therefore, the entire state.
In this case the answer is clearly yes.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and ubiquitous, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the area of corruption, in mutual favors, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: State ministries, in the absence of financial means, entrust the drafting of bills to private legal companies, which are often linked to industry.
These types of bills are then passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
In this way, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation quickly find themselves in a situation like that described by Appiános in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the Time of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state had long been disintegrating and the administrations were occupied by force."
In exchange for bribes, favors obtained illegitimately and help to finance stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption spread unhindered and people went to the polls with the vote spoken in advance"... "there were no people of character who aspired to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state went eight months without consuls"... "Although it began to talk seriously that the only remedy for such a serious situation was the autocracy and that it was necessary to choose "
The conclusion, as in ancient times, is that today’s society is based on inconsiderate preferences of individual benefit without regard to common interests.
Private capital is not able, in its essence, to understand and claim the benefits of the whole society.
The result is the same as then, an unprecedented decline of the elite, without an effort being made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, waiting for the next coup.
The truly devastating fact is that today’s elite completely ignore the hundreds of thousands of lives lost, the social and humanitarian catastrophes we have witnessed, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them in ancient and most recent history.
Suspending the law on public awards is not the solution; at least not in the long run.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue looking for other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution lies in concrete socio-political reforms, which reinforce both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
