Argo Movie: If It Gets Raw, Call Hollywood
In November 1979 a protest group of Islamist students occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned Shah Mohamed Réza Páhlevi, who after the revolution fled to the United States, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration the situation offered no positive prospect: throwing the shah overboard could not be allowed, since, if it did, it endangered the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which subsequently escalated further with the failed attempt to release the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government’s negotiating intervention.
In the US, their fate caused a wave of solidarity and animosity against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck themed an episode of this story, which garnered a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees of the building escaped.
After a difficult journey, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, for it helped a cover story an extravagant point: they came out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team that examined the location in the country for the filming of a science fiction blockbuster.
Combination of genres
The plan devised by “exfiltration” expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood collaboration.
To make the lie seem truthful, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society even had a real office.
Details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck’s film is a singular combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a hoax (an example can be the series Ocean's Eleven).
The film combines moods. We find on the one hand well-documented sequences of Tehran. In the sequence of credits are shown emblematic photographs of the time of the events, which were embodied in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes somewhat lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And also, scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions: men in suits who analyze the situation at the negotiating table, in the corridors of the office, by phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is her third feature film, after "Goodbye Little, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it’s the first Affleck film in which the action has no place in the city of Boston, where he grew up.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck proves it in Argo, where Tehran “rolls” in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of true events. The introductory sequence of the seizure of the embassy is impressive for its synoptic capacity that, at the same time, conveys the emotion of bewilderment and lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, the story takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the impostor team in Tehran’s bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story doesn’t offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
Sometimes it adds something to the reality: everything doesn’t come out so elegantly here (the scene where the crisis lurks at Tehran’s airport, the diversion of a call to America, and the unbridled search behind its trail turn into madness).
Argo’s weakness is the lack of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not, by any means, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck’s film loses a bit of dramatic stroke, but it is a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, value its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70s.
But if it collapses, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a true story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of the secret services can be, it is enough.
