The architecture studio MVRDV shows that true adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the library of Spijkenisse and the newly completed "mountain of books" - 2 photos
“I think the building is fun, it has a futuristic look to it, and there’s finally something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by walking down the street.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company located near the library, points out: “Plus, the building is nice.”
But I wonder why we need a library these days.
We all have the Internet, tablets and e-books.
Nobody goes into those old-fashioned libraries for pleasure, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeper city at the gates of Rotterdam hardly worth a quick visit, has the dubious honour of having set a record for forgetting.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counteract this shameful situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges that are represented on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that’s how policy makers decided there was only one way to improve statistics: you had to build a library!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar charts and responsible for fun as well as cynical buildings, took the subject with his usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked perplexed around him and shrugged, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, the so-called 'Boekenberg'".
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain rises to its intended location.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential and townhouse buildings.
In early November the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small town devoid of history, which to date had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would intuit rather a dairy plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a cheese maker.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountain massif, but true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with its topography at every step of their climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the annealed brick floor and the elegant street lamps unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
When you look up, you can see the benches of the park, the dogs and the children playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally the bookshelves are arranged along the facade and in the center opens a huge dark room that is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
What we have done is turn the classic spatial configuration upside down and take the reading area from the interior to the exterior.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserves the black shelves that assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and railing at the same time.
The sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even the most up-to-date architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in the city of Spijkenisse.
And that’s how one day, on a Frisian farm, we came across the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in the greenhouses and fields of the Netherlands, a plastic fabric of a few millimeters in thickness has been used as a base to hold the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This tissue lasts for two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, until plates of four centimeters thick were obtained.
With the heat and pressure, so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a mix of new car and sneaker.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but in it you can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere while maintaining the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a New Soul
“Although it’s hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project when it comes to ecology,” says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling is obtained from geothermal energy.
Even though the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden trusses located transversely to the glass facade serve to shade and absorb most of the sun’s rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there, too.
Traditional Chinese medicine professor Cynthia Bogarde has also visited the library, calling the "Boekenberg" the "late soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way, it is intended to fill, for the moment, the optical holes of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; at present it has 70,000 copies.
The concept has taken a deep dive.
The shelves are full.
“There’s nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows that your book is part of the library.
Even if it's just there to decorate.
In this way, the MVRDV studio has achieved great success in that discipline that in specialized slang is known as "creation of an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
Regardless of how young and uneducated you may be.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
Szabo: "The Germans must play a more leading role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, this puts Berlin in a rather thorny diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier in the week, Germany implied that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories observer status to the United Nations.
However, Berlin eventually abstained.
Why is that?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, because of the special relationship that unites the country with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time, I don’t think he supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to prove its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yes, it is.
This is because it is currently reorienting its foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to doing so.
I think they are still groping over what their role will be, but they have already started on the path to a “normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries like France or Great Britain.
What does a “normal” foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy finds a strong motivation in economic policy, that is, in exports and in its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers and that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the stance taken on the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason it must be careful not to alienate itself from Arab public opinion or Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not give it so much importance since it is not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a key role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the U.S. by refraining from voting on important decisions such as the Palestine vote?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that there has been such a drastic break as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps Germany has gained some respect for it.
After all, all this has only shown that it is a country that is taken seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
In Europe there are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative.
Instead, the U.S. has been clearly in favor of a veto.
Is there a disparity of opinion between the U.S. and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of U.S. domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration secretly shows a great understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot publicly defend this position.
I believe that the true disparity of opinions does not really have the magnitude attributed to it.
If we analyze the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policy he develops.
