"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a globally known brand and Polo Ralph Lauren as well.
What is Armani Polo?
Behind this name is a name officially registered in China but that has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the true eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
And even then it is not clear that they will be given the reason.
“Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China,” says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing who specializes in Far Eastern rights violations.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
The imitators simply add a couple of letters to be able to register their marks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and in place of Prada Prada-Kny is registered.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as has happened to the sports goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet in which he keeps seats of the Beijing trademark office.
On 14 September 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the trademark Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that also used the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities there are large multi-storey stores dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch’s cases are of a different kind: on behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
This refers to women who have "fished" a rich man.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
“It’s bad for the business, you have to fight it,” Pattloch says.
“The brand is watering down, the monopolistic position disappears, and the damage to the image is enormous.”
The financial losses and the procedural costs of the sectors affected are millions, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from market analysis firm CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros per year China is, in size, the third market for luxury goods and the fastest growing.
However, the cancellation of registrations of dubious legality in the registration of trademarks is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
Processes can last up to nine years and the outcome is uncertain.
Pattloch talks about cases in which the court dismissed a lawsuit because so much time had elapsed that the name subject of the lawsuit had already become a “market reality.”
“If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarist because the process has damaged his brand in China,” Pattloch said.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That is why today the Chinese can still use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
Volvo buyer Geely initially used a blue-and-white logo that was largely reminiscent of BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
The clothing manufacturer Lacoste lost in China against imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo represented a crocodile looking in the opposite direction from the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO brand office in Beijing recognizes that in 2010 they have had difficulties due to the shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, “the work emergency situation returned to normal.”
In this way, the number of unprocessed claim processes has been reduced by 22%.
Almost 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims remain outstanding.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As usual in China, the numbers are staggering.
Last year, the CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
It would be a new record and means that China leads the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth consecutive year, according to the trademark office.
It seems that this also happens with the number of valid logos, a figure that amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan in royalties would have been pocketed.
Put another way, this means that on average each inscription costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese imitator.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the imitator has managed to secure the Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“We have caused this situation ourselves because in Germany the surnames are not protected,” says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The trademark office CTMO also dismissed the appeal from the Munichs.
Freudenberg has been proved right in the next two instances, but the other side is still fighting today.
You have to be very careful
Now the case has reached the doors of the High Court of Justice, where it remains pending resolution.
Wentzler is confident that he can resolve the issue favorably and praises the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that “the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time.”
Internal costs are difficult to estimate; the corporate archive has had to review records up to 100 years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposing party a “six-figure sum in euros” with the aim of reaching an amicable settlement, but it was unsuccessful.
“It shows how much we care,” Wentzler says.
The dangers lurking in the Far East threaten even to affect Europe.
In particular, if the imitators secure the rights to unprotected trademarks there.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
The group has long since abandoned this commercial area, but nevertheless managed to prevent registration.
“You have to be very careful,” Wentzler says.
Both he and lawyer Pattloch advise German companies to be extremely cautious when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark law, but what needs to be done is "to register in China also everything that may be susceptible to protection", as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the issue can be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, should Freudenberg lose the last round of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party license fees in his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
