The tour of the Talysh mountain region could be described as wild and romantic.
The minibus roars along the winding road that passes wooded hills, high-flowing rivers and the simple homes of local farmers.
Everything is green and juicy, one might even think that it is located in the Black Forest.
However, we are in the southernmost part of Azerbaijan; from here the border with Iran is only a few kilometers away.
Here live the "talyshi", a people that not much is known, apart from the fact that they dominate Persian and Azeri perfectly and that they are very long-lived.
Our final destination is Lerik.
This small town boasts perhaps overly massive architecture designed in the Soviet era and does not seem to fit into such a picturesque mountain landscape.
European tourists barely reach this place, since the road from the capital of Azerbaijan, Baku, is too heavy.
To travel the 323 kilometers that separate both urban centers, it takes eight hours because the road is one way.
The astonishing wealth that the country enjoys thanks to oil from the Caspian Sea has not yet reached this remote region.
However, Pilata Fatulayeva (48) is convinced that Lerik has what it takes to become a tourist attraction.
“Baku became famous in May to celebrate the Eurovision Song Contest and next year we will celebrate the World’s Oldest People Festival,” says Fatulayeva.
She is the director of the Museum of Longevity, perhaps the only one in the world.
The life of eight dozen talyshis over 100 years old is documented here. Fatulayeva points to a black and white image.
This is my grandfather, who lived 120 years.
His son died at the age of 136.
However, the undisputed star of the museum is the sheepherder ?irali M?sl?mov, who seems to have lived 168 years.
However, there is no birth certificate that certifies it.
And if we take into account that the oldest man documented lived 122 years, it seems that the age of M?sl?mov is quite suspicious.
“He was born in the region in 1805 and died in 1973,” Fatulayeva explains.
The man was married three times and had 23 children, and apparently still had time to conceive one more daughter at the age of 136.
Have you made a mistake then in your age in a couple of decades?
However, Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, has also heard about the advanced age of this Central Asian inhabitant.
“In some regions of China, Japan or in the Hunza Valley in Pakistan there are also very elderly people,” says Scholz, “even in Sardinia there are many older men.”
Due to the lack of documentation, it is impossible to provide scientific evidence about age, especially when there is no civil record.
Everyday glasses filled with melted butter
It is a fact that, surprisingly often, the inhabitants of the region around Lerik often reach a biblical age.
There are currently 20 people over the age of 100.
Why do so many elderly people live here in the south?
Azerbaijani tour guide Farid Mugimzadeh explains that these are the special genes of the talyshis.
The director of the museum, Ms Fatulayeva, believes instead that the cause lies in food.
However, from a nutritional point of view, it does not seem logical that precisely the high-calorie diet of the talyshi, who love meat, bread and especially dairy products and many of whom, in addition, drink a glass of melted butter daily, is so healthy.
Or perhaps it is the natural way of life that keeps people young? In Cengemiran, a small settlement not far from the town of Lerik lives Rubaba Mirzayeva.
At 97 years old he is relatively young for what is stylized by these latitudes.
Mirzayeva, who claims to have 143 descendants, lives in a simple wooden house typical of the entire Caucasus region.
Sitting on the floor, she untiringly moves a huge tub of butter.
Eight people live under one roof, including one of Mirzayeva’s sons and a daughter, both of whom became grandparents long ago.
Two small children also jump from one side to the other.
In the kitchen they prepare tea for the guests, a tea that they serve in typical glasses with a bulging shape.
Mirzayeva’s teeth are white and perfectly aligned and under the scarf she hides two long braids of dark blond hair that her son proudly reveals to us.
I have always washed my hair with milk, so it has never fallen out and has kept its color.
“I haven’t used a shampoo either,” Mirzayeva says.
The pension is enough to live on.
He has always eaten only what he produced on his own farm: tomatoes, potatoes and peas.
