Then she tells us about her husband, who was in the army.
The worst was the post-World War II era.
However, everything returned to its course when the "dear father", Heydar Aliyew, took control of the situation.
This kind of propaganda sounds weird on an older woman’s lips.
In Azerbaijan, however, the cult of the father figure of the nation, who runs his country like a dictator, knows no bounds.
He remained in power until 2003, at which time he ceded the witness to his son Ilham.
At least the elderly in Azerbaijan do not know what poverty is.
Mirzayeva charges 230 manat (about the same amount in euros) as a monthly pension, an amount with which you can live well considering the situation here.
