Rakfisk is salted trout that is left to ferment in water for, depending on how foul-smelling you prefer, up to a year.
As it gets darker and colder, Norwegians flock to a festival held here in Fagernes, dedicated to this most, so to speak, captivating delicacy.
“You eat raw and then you drink a glass of aquavit from a drink,” says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also what is known as the “General of Rakfisk,” who is in charge of organizing the festival.
