College students aren’t attacked for their views just now
I don’t remember any time in my life when I hadn’t been dreaming of getting a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had been in what I assumed was the best place in the world to learn, a contemporary-era Greek symposium that fostered the two pillars of civilization: free thought and tolerance.
However, within two weeks of taking up my place at Worcester College in the late 1980s to pursue a career in History, I had already packed my bags, which triggered the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and burst into tears.
My friends were bewildered.
The Evening Standard claimed that I had dropped out because I couldn’t stand some college classmates having sex in the next room.
Writer A. N. Wilson jokingly announced that I was gone because I was forced to drink in peeled cups.
The truth was less fun.
I ran away from there.
Yes, I fled, because I had been subjected to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my outlandish name, or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was harassed for only one reason, which in the cradle of the supposed illustration was somewhat intolerant and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a prominent adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the Conservative party.
You may wonder what that is all about now.
