At other universities, conservative students say they are being treated as “Turkish heads” by the introduction of higher tuition fees.
Luke Black, 20, a vice president of the University of Nottingham’s Conservative Party Association, said in a Sunday newspaper that “there is a growing left-wing trend in universities.
People assume we’re like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing each other.”
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old history student at Corpus Christi who filed the motion for greater protection, says this environment is “uncomfortable,” while Stephanie Cherill, 19, president-elect of the OUCA, says the attitude of JCR members toward people who are center-right has worsened.
“This poses a threat to the environment of intellectual debate, as well as to the well-being of members,” he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford I was more lonely than one.
I entered college in September 1986, I was a terribly shy 18-year-old.
Hatred of the Conservative Party was at an all-time high.
The previous year, the university had voted to deny Margaret Thatcher, a former student, an "honoris causa" degree following cuts in higher education funding.
The atmosphere would have made any Stalinist shudder.
Already during the first days of the week of welcoming the new university students, when the new students meet and meet the professors, I received a sign of the bitterness that awaited me.
I found that professors not only turned a blind eye to the mockery of conservative college students, but willingly participated in it.
The miners’ strike policy, privatization and the government’s opposition to anti-apartheid sanctions in South Africa all made their way to the seminary’s wooden rooms.
The first one I attended had to be translated into English French texts of the eighteenth century and I was not prepared for what came next.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I didn't say one.
Pitt, a short man with a face that looked like cake dough, knew well how to expel bad bile.
“Do the Thatcherites refuse to learn French, or are they just fools?” he asked.
The other students laughed.
My eyes burned with the tears I was trying to hold back.
“I suggest you go to French classes in your spare time, as long as you’re not too busy meeting people,” growled Pitt.
I returned to my room as a soul in sorrow.
That night I sat alone at dinnertime in college; then I felt a slight pat on the back.
He was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of OUCA.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
"I'm afraid that's how it goes.
They mess with anyone suspected of being Tory.
For me it's very complicated, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so for you it will be even worse.
Many Tories newcomers appear to be Labour."
Later, in a local pub, I cowardly tried to hide.
I insisted that I disagreed with everything Mrs Thatcher said.
That trick proved useless.
A freshman in Philosophy, Politics and Economics who, paradoxically, had studied at Eton, said: “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contaminated."
Other students adopted this song.
I became the dirty pervert.
