I felt the same way homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the 1960s.
Could he ever lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to meet people who thought like me only after dark?
Should I become a Labourer and repress my natural tendencies?
The three years that awaited me were presented as a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only openly Tory professor was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History for my college.
They hated her for being not only a Conservative, but also a foreign policy adviser to Thatcher and one of the people who wrote her speeches.
I was barely there.
He detested the place because he considered it provincial and insignificant and because of its adherence to the Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
