The Hardest Craft in the World: The Human Mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the Indonesian volcano’s porters risk their lives and health carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to descend every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulfurous gas that emanates from the bowels of the Earth solidifies when it comes in contact with the air.
After pulling large sulfur rocks, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two bamboo baskets that he carries on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters in altitude, but the exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to ascend at a turtle pace, keeping the balance and measuring their steps carefully so as not to slip and fall down the cliff.
They know that any mishap could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the cliffs of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
Once up, they make their way among the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, wearisomely carrying the heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters of height.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better said, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euro) for each kilo of sulfur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, since this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
“As is normal to carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip,” explains Anto, who usually carries out three daily shipments.
It takes three hours in each and ends up grinding, but they allow you to collect 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a pittance for such an inhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn on the field.
“The miners’ day is very high here, where coffee collection is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” clarifies the porter, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the cut was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as forceful as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I have brought her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathes hard, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At 27 years old, Anto has been playing hide in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to take its toll despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases emitted by the volcano.
It’s the price you have to pay to achieve your dream.
"I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished for life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing an filthy wooden cabin with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Challenging the shadows, Anto descends into the crater with a small lantern attached to his helmet, which he has bought himself with his money.
About 400 porters carry sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its great profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs or provide any equipment to the porters, who work on their own and at both weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera that, together with the entry of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is for the beasts and not for the people,” protests Madrusin, a burly 42-year-old porter who has been at Kawah Ijen for three decades, since he left school.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, he says he will endure working “as much as he can” because he needs the money to educate his three children, between 18 and 10 years old.
I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano has been my whole life.
Although sulfur burns the throat and stings the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that none complain of suffering serious diseases ... beyond, of course, of their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pains in the knees and sores on the shoulders, which have been malformed by the weight of the baskets.
Swinging the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Each day, he and his companions pluck 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a goat path in the undergrowth.
“I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life,” proclaims Unainik opening his mouth well, where he is missing several teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30, also works on sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the toughest trades in the world: the one made by the human mules of Kawah Ijen.
Singapore seeks babies to save economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress and the cost of property and education for not having children.
"Singapore's population needs to grow."
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife, we do our civic duty and we create life!
It may seem implausible that these verses are part of a peppermint pill ad, but despite that – or perhaps because of that – the video went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The phrases are part of a rap that uses local references such as "Let's put a bao in the oven" to laugh at Singapore's birth rate.
The advertising company that made the video, BBH, hopes that with the announcement they will be able to draw attention to the problem in a fun way.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to do “their national duty.”
This is purely an internet thing, so we had to make it fun and funny.
It's the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world to reproduce ourselves, so we felt this was an issue we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried many things, such as throwing perfumes with pheromones or organizing speed-dating evenings.
Many of those ideas may have been creative, but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we thought, why don’t we do as creatively as possible to solve this problem, which is to compose a rap?
1.2 children
The one who doesn’t take it so lightly is the Singaporean government.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for marriages and parents gives up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its leaders’ conservatism and strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate, according to its national population division, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 – known as the replacement rate – was in 1976.
So why don’t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policy for the National Population Division, says it’s because of “better education” and “a wider range of career opportunities.”
“That has allowed people to have a wider range of choices in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond getting married and raising a family,” she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to increased singleness, and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a declining birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy that aims to dramatically increase immigration to cope with the population decline has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that abound with barely disguised xenophobia against many new immigrants, particularly Chinese, whom they criticize for keeping wages low and not integrating.
Rising immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore’s ruling party last year experienced its worst election result since independence.
Since the elections there has been an attempt to correct the problem, with higher quotas and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the drop in the birth rate has known effects on a nation’s economic growth, tax revenues, healthcare costs and immigration policies, Singapore’s example is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it has begun to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authority has gone on to control the number of small apartments, known as “shoeboxes,” that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have been very successful in sales.
However, there are concerns that they may promote a singleness lifestyle and discourage developers who want to build large, family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of real estate firm EL Developers, says his “shoeboxes” sell much faster than larger units.
They are more popular, in the sense that units sell out days, even weeks, faster than larger units.
This makes it much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new rules give clearer guidance for developers, who were previously hampered if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a state city.
While these new rules may be a step toward increasing the national birth rate, talking to Singaporeans working in the downtown financial district seems like they won’t have much effect.
“People are very stressed, houses are expensive and so is education, so many people are putting it off,” says one young executive.
Other people may have children.
“But for me it’s important to have my own money and time,” says another young man in his 20s.
Men and women cite their careers, stress, and the cost of property and education as the reasons that keep them from having children.
So, as much as the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans have the last word.
