Unasur Summit ends without making public the Lima Declaration
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (UNASUR) concluded today in Peru without making public the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven attending leaders.
Efe repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of the Unasur, but sources of Foreign Ministry and Presidency initially indicated that they were going to deliver it after the closure, but later said that at some point it will be published on the website of the Peruvian Government.
When consulted by the text, they pointed out that the content had been exposed by the president of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during a brief statement to the press.
Journalists’ access to Summit information was restricted at all times.
During the day only the soundless video of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among the reporters was delivered by the press spokespeople of some of the governments of the Unasur attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian.
The only document released during the day was the list of attending presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who requested greater data.
Subsequently, the Presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the “final declaration” of the summit, but it is Humala’s pronouncement, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America-Arab Countries (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently requested by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration that they had previously announced was also not disseminated.
On the official ASPA website it can be corroborated that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international events, Peruvian authorities made efforts to ensure that transmission systems were in place for all journalists but limited information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a ruling by the Court of The Hague that settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (ICJ), which begins on Monday in The Hague to listen to the allegations of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
“We will abide by and execute the judgment that defines the differences that we are bringing to this international court today,” Humala said, along with his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties and international tribunals,” Piñera added, and greeted Humala with a handshake, alongside the two countries’ flags.
The confirmation of both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Pact of Bogotá by which it had agreed to submit to the rulings of that international tribunal, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered seriously wrong.
The summit was held with the absences of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the ouster of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit, shortly after noon in Lima.
The president read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and the lines of action were set for 31 projects between the South American countries for a total of 17 billion dollars in investments.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of UNASUR will take "important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship for which we are expanding the agreements on residence."
He reported that actions are being promoted to improve “cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, low-cost internet access in all corners of South America, and jointly and efficiently address the risks of natural disasters.”
With Europe in crisis, “the economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must serve to expand our productive matrix and envision a better future for our peoples,” Humala added.
"We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of the spaces of South America, especially in rural areas and borders ... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," the Peruvian president said in a message read.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located in the transverse axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give more details.
The final document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for his reinstatement to the Union of South American Nations,” from which he is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated, and good relations between neighbors, was another of the issues highlighted by the summit.
In this regard, the president of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he expected to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to treat in a respectful way the maritime dispute after a ruling of the ICJ, questioned by Bogotá.
“Tomorrow (Saturday) you may have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega,” Santos said.
“We are going to review all these roads, they are not exclusive, even the treaty with Nicaragua is going to require a conversation with Nicaragua,” he stressed.
“With President Ortega, I hope to be able to tell him that we handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,” Santos said.
Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico where they plan to attend the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the bloc’s defense ministers met earlier to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defense in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the last country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
